5. Multilevel analysis

2023-06-13

Back to content page

Learning objective

  • Recognize situations where multilevel models are needed to describe the data with a hierarchical structure dependent data/observations where multilevel model is needed
  • Estimate and interpret effects under hierarchical linear model
  • Perform model selection for hierarchical linear model

1 Multilevel models

What is MLM

Class of models which can handle grouped/clustered data which are not independent (data with nested structure)

  • Different names:
    • Multilevel models (MLM)
    • Hierarchical level model (HLM)
    • Random effects/intercept/slope model
    • Mixed-effects model (fixed + random effects)
  • Why MLM?
    • Research question might have a multi-level structure, e.g. household – household members; ward – patients
    • Observations not independent, correlated within units. This violates linear regression assumptions and leads to biased estimates of standard error/uncertainty. Need to allow for dependence for correct inference.
    • Interested in both contextual and individual effects, e.g. want to know difference between countries.
  • Consequence of ignoring multi-level structures
    • Ecological fallacy: Implications from group not always applicable to individual level
    • Atomistic fallacy: May miss important group effects
    • Inflated type 1 error: effective sample size < actual sample size (If the observations are dependent, even if u have N samples, u get info from less than N samples). Lead to underestimation of the uncertainty or standard error (p-values too small)
    • Loss of statistical power: Reduce signal-to-noise ratio (miss signals from grouping – Sometimes grouping contain information, miss some independent variable/covariant)

Model formula

Fixed vs random effects models

  1. Fixed effects
    • Used when
      1. Interested in group-level estimates, especially when the number of groups is small (not practical if large, e.g. thousands of household categories).
      2. Need to adjust for the confounding group-level effects
    • Less efficient as more parameters are needed (Difficult to be significant because u are estimating more things)
    • Assumed conditional independence (After conditioning on grouping, the individuals are independent => error terms are independent)
  2. Random effects
    • Used when
      • Groups are regarded as a random sample from a greater population, especially when the number of groups is large
      • E.g. households are not systematically different but happens randomly (higher/lower income), i.e. different in household 1 and 2 is not research interest
    • More efficient but vulnerable to bias.
    • Assumption: The random effects need to be uncorrelated to the other covariates of the model.

Hierarichical linear model

Estimation procedure for ICC and design effect (R)

Estimate variables

  • Need to estimate \(\gamma, \sigma^2 \text{ and } \tau^2\). In analysis we want unbiased estimate => use REML but when we do likelihood ratio test => use ML
  1. Maximum likelihood (ML)
    • \(\hat{\gamma}\) as a function of \(\sigma^2 \text{ and } \tau^2\)
    • Numerical maximization is needed
    • Used when likelihood ratio test is carried out
  2. Restricted maximum likelihood (REML)
    • Variance for ML estimate is biased/underestimated (problematic) because the denominator is n instead of (n-1). So REML corrects for the loss in degrees of freedom (using n - p as denominator where p is no. of predictor) and produces unbiased variance estimates
    • Preferred when sample size is small (uncertainty is more important)

Estimate ICC and design effect

  • ICC measures the proportion of variance explained by the between group variance

  • Design effect measure the variance of your dataset compared to variance obtained from simple random sampling

require(ICC)
n.group <- 10
y <- 1:1000 #Type 1. Groupings by sorted values
group <- rep(1:n.group, each=length(y)/n.group) #Group assignments: first 100 to gp1, 2nd 100 to gp 2 etc
rand.y <- sample(y, length(y), replace=F) #Type 2. Grouping randomly assigned/shuffled

## ICC for two groups
ICCest(as.factor(group), y) #ICC close to 1 = grouping is informative
ICCest(as.factor(group), rand.y) #ICC close to 0 = grouping has no information

Background

    • There may also be hospital-level factors (e.g. hospital size) affecting mlos
    • Data were collected from 200 mothers from each of the 12 hospitals. Age: 20-45y. Hospital size: small, medium, large

Linear mixed model (LMM) / HLM (R)

  • Package: lme4
  • lmer(formula, REML=TRUE, offset, subset, data)
    • formula…fixed effects specification similar to lm(), random effects: (RE_var|group)
    • REML=TRUE …for restricted maximum likelihood, otherwise maximum likelihood method will be used for the estimation
    • offset, subset, data …as usual
  • glmer() for generalized linear mixed-effects model (GLMM)

A. Random intercept model (R)

## Random intercept Model
require(lme4)
hlm.los1 <- lmer(los ~ 1 + (1|hosp), data=mlos) 
summary(hlm.los1)
## Linear mixed model fit by REML ['lmerMod']
## Formula: los ~ 1 + (1 | hosp)
##    Data: mlos
## 
## REML criterion at convergence: 2569.9
## 
## Scaled residuals:

## 
## Random effects:
##  Groups   Name        Variance Std.Dev.
##  hosp     (Intercept) 0.2576   0.5076  
##  Residual             0.1659   0.4073  
## Number of obs: 2400, groups:  hosp, 12
## 
## Fixed effects:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value
## (Intercept)   3.1676     0.1468   21.58
# We have Fixed effect intercept + random effect hospital + error term (residual)
# The estimated overall mean of maternity LOS is 3.2 days
# ICC = 0.2576 / (0.2576+0.1659) = 0.61. Large variation between hospitals (grouping informative)

## Residual after fitting model (accounting for random effect)
with(mlos,plot(summary(hlm.los1)$residuals ~ hosp,ylim=c(-3,3),cex=0.5, las=1))

#No obvious clustering of residuals by hospitals (no pattern of residual/error term, the mean is 0)

Bii. Test fixed effects

We should test for fixed effects’ significance.

  1. t-test
    • Need to calculate the appropriate degree of freedom becoz dataset is dependent
    • Use package lmerTest (will replace lmer() in the package lme4)
    • Unload the package: detach("package:lmerTest", unload=TRUE)
  2. Likelihood ratio test (preferred)
    • Need to be nested models(?don’t understand)
    • For fixed effect
      • Use likelihood from maximum likelihood estimation (ML instead of REML) REML=FALSE in lmer()). Then use anova() to do LRT
      • H0: \(\gamma_{10}=0\) i.e. whether regression coefficient of predictor (e.g. age) is 0 or not
    • For random intercept effect (see next subpage)
      • Use likelihood from maximum likelihood estimation (ML instead of REML) REML=FALSE in lmer()) for MLM. Use logLik() to obtain the log-likelihood for simple linear regression.
      • H0: \(\tau^2=0\) vs H1: \(\tau^2>0\)

  1. Simulation (very complicated method)
## T-test
require(lmerTest)
hlm.los2 <- lmer(los ~ age + (1|hosp), data=mlos)
summary(hlm.los2)
# Note df not integer (12.54) becoz dataset is dependent (effective sample size < actual sample size)
# Age is not significant (p-val = 0.175)

Extra. Test random intercept

We can use LRT to test for random intercept effect too!

## LRT
lm.los20 <- lm(los ~ age, data=mlos) #simple linear regression -- age without random intercept model
#recall that "hlm.los2.ml" is age with random intercept model
lrt <- as.numeric(2*abs(logLik(lm.los20)-logLik(hlm.los2.ml))) #compute likelihood ratio using the formula
pchisq(lrt, df=1, lower.tail=F) #compute p-val
# P-val = 0 so reject null hypothesis. Random intercept model is selected.
## [1] 0

Model comparison

  • R2 difficult to compare when there are random effects.
  • May use AIC, BIC, deviance, etc. Note only valid for models using ML (REML=FALSE)
hlm.los1.ml <- lmer(los ~ 1 + (1|hosp), data=mlos, REML=F) 
AIC(hlm.los1.ml, hlm.los2.ml, hlm.los3, hlm.los4)
##             df      AIC
## hlm.los1.ml  3 2573.852
## hlm.los2.ml  4 2574.008
## hlm.los3     6 2577.936
## hlm.los4     8 2577.887
# Model with random intercept (model 1) and is selected coz lowest AIC (2573)
# Only AIC difference > 5 can indicates superiority. So we cannnot say model 1 is better than 3 and 4.

3 Model diagnostics

  • Compare fitted and observed values
  1. Residual plot
    • Residuals by predictors (to assess incorrect specification)
      e.g., residuals by hospitals
    • Residuals by predicted value (to assess potential heteroskedasticity)
      I.e. error/variance with predicted value
  2. qqplot for normality of the random effects
    • We assumed normal distribution for random effects.
  3. qqmath()
  4. Level-2 (group) diagnostics not covered
## Heteroscedasticity -- Residuals by fitted values
plot(hlm.los2, resid(.)~fitted(.))

# No obvious heteroskedasticity. Variance don't change with fitted values (range always in 0.5 to -0.5)

## Linearaltiy -- Residuals by age (we assume age to be linear)
plot(hlm.los2, resid(., scaled=TRUE) ~ age | hosp, abline = 0)

# No obvious nonlinearity
# If it's nonlinearity, we may falsely conclude either significant or non-significant. So still need to test altho age is insignficant in this example.

## QQ plot for the random effects -- Residuals against normal quantiles
qqmath(hlm.los2)

# Normality assumption looks valid. Diagonal line.

Review

  • Multilevel models can describe the dependence between observations with hierarchical structure
  • Provide unbiased estimates for the standard error for correct inference (e.g., age is insignificant after accounting for hospital effect)
  • Can use fixed or random effects for the group-level effects
  • Selection of models and testing of parameters can be carried out using likelihood ratio test

Real-life example

  • Home-based Hospice Care reduced end-of-life expenditure in Taiwan by Chen et. al, Medicine 2015
    • Objective: to examine the impact of home-based hospisc care on end-of-life medical expenditure
    • Subject: 78,613 cancer decedents in Taiwan
    • HLM used to account for potential clustering effect by hospitals
      • Result: Home-based hospice care associated with a lower EOF medical expenditure
      • Lower hospital spending index associates with less effect of home-based hospice care (tho it is just ‘nuisance’ parameters coz the researchers not interested in the effect)
